==Modern adaptations==
There have been many [[Native Americans in children's literature|children's]] and picture books that recount traditional Raven Tales. These new versions have been criticized for portraying a much "nicer" Raven with little left from the original greedy [[trickster]]. In some stories Raven acts for the good of people and not for himself. In other stories Raven refuses to use force, and sexual themes are edited out. Trickery is in some instances substituted for magic. These newer tales are also written in conventions of Western rather than Native American literature thus conveying the message that native storytellers' ability or style is inferior.<ref name="Singer">{{cite web|url=https://www.msu.edu/user/singere/fakelore.html|title=Fakelore, Multiculturalism, and the Ethics of Children's Literature|last=Singer|first=Eliot A.}}</ref>

In 2004, The [[Smithsonian Institution]] sponsored [[Chris Kientz]] to develop a series of half-hour animated television programs targeted at school children as an entertaining way of educating kids on aboriginal folklore.  The show ''[[Raven Tales (TV series)|Raven Tales]]'' was produced by New Machine Studios working with producer Winadzi James and aired for two seasons with a total of 26 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Award-Winning Animated Series|url=http://www.raventales.com/|publisher=RavenTales (Alberta) Ltd|accessdate=1 September 2014|year=2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Raven Tales Episode Guide|url=http://www.smithsonianchannel.com/sc/web/series/731/raven-tales|website=Smithsonian Channel|publisher=SNI/SI Networks L.L.C|accessdate=1 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903144001/http://www.smithsonianchannel.com/sc/web/series/731/raven-tales|archive-date=3 September 2014|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In 2010, Matt Dembicki produced an anthological graphic novel of the trickster stories, making sure to maintain the cultural integrity of the stories with the help of 21 Native American  story-tellers who were paired directly with several graphic designers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Higgins|first1=Jim|title='Trickster Tales': Gladstone, Indian storytellers team with artists|url=http://missoulian.com/lifestyles/territory/trickster-tales-gladstone-indian-storytellers-team-with-artists/article_f517b738-7016-11df-a81d-001cc4c03286.html|publisher=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref>

